<para id="eip-id3148820">What double-slit separation would produce a first-order maximum at <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>3</m:mn><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mtext>00º</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> for 25.0-keV x rays? The small answer indicates that the wave character of x rays is best determined by having them interact with very small objects such as atoms and molecules.</para></problem></exercise>
    <exercise id="fs-id3450401" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id3450402">    <para id="import-auto-id2400659"><title>Integrated Concepts </title></para>
<para id="eip-id1616692">In a laboratory experiment designed to duplicate Thomson’s determination of <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>q</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mi>e</m:mi></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">/</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mi>e</m:mi></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math>, a beam of electrons having a velocity of <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>6</m:mn><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mtext>00</m:mtext><m:mo stretchy="false">×</m:mo><m:msup><m:mtext>10</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mn>7</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mrow><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mtext>m/s</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> enters a <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mtext>5.00</m:mtext><m:mo stretchy="false">×</m:mo><m:msup><m:mtext>10</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo><m:mn>3</m:mn></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mrow><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mtext>T</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> magnetic field. The beam moves perpendicular to the field in a path having a 6.80-cm radius of curvature. Determine <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>q</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mi>e</m:mi></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">/</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mi>e</m:mi></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> from these observations, and compare the result with the known value.</para></problem>
